ground_truth:
Regularization is a technique used to prevent overfitting in machine learning models by adding a penalty term to the loss function. In logistic regression, there are two common types of regularization: L1 and L2 regularization. 

L1 regularization adds a penalty term to the loss function that is proportional to the absolute value of the weights. This results in sparse weight vectors where some of the weights are exactly zero, effectively performing feature selection. The C# code for implementing L1 regularization in logistic regression using the Accord.NET library is as follows:

```csharp
var teacher = new LogisticRegressionLearning()
{
 Learner = (p) => new IterativeReweightedLeastSquares()
 {
 MaxIterations = 100,
 Tolerance = 1e-4,
 Regularization = 1.0, // Set the regularization parameter here
 RegularizationType = RidgeRegressionMethod.L1 // Use L1 regularization here
 }
};
```

L2 regularization, also known as Ridge regression, adds a penalty term to the loss function that is proportional to the squared magnitude of the weights. This results in smaller weight values overall and can lead to better generalization performance. The C# code for implementing L2 regularization in logistic regression using the Accord.NET library is as follows:

```csharp
var teacher = new LogisticRegressionLearning()
{
 Learner = (p) => new IterativeReweightedLeastSquares()
 {
 MaxIterations = 100,
 Tolerance = 1e-4,
 Regularization = 1.0, // Set the regularization parameter here
 RegularizationType = RidgeRegressionMethod.Ridge // Use L2 regularization here
 }
};
```

To choose the optimal regularization parameter, you can use cross-validation to evaluate the performance of the model on a validation set for different values of the regularization parameter. This will allow you to select the value of the regularization parameter that gives the best performance on the validation set.

